            <fr:title text="Towards univalent reference types › side effects in programming languages"><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00OI.xml" title="Towards univalent reference types" addr="jms-00OI" type="local"><html:em><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2024-univalent.xml" title="Towards univalent reference types" addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2024-univalent" type="local">Towards <html:strong>univalent</html:strong> reference types</fr:link></html:em></fr:link> › side effects in programming languages</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Slide</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Most practical programming languages have <html:strong><html:em>side effects</html:em></html:strong>: state, input-output, errors, etc.</html:p><beamer:pause xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" /><html:p><html:strong><html:em>Monads</html:em></html:strong> capture the structure of side effects (<fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/moggi-1991.xml" title="Notions of computation and monads" addr="moggi-1991" type="local">Moggi</fr:link>, <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/philipwadler.xml" title="Philip Wadler" addr="philipwadler" type="local">Wadler</fr:link>).</html:p>
 <jms-indent:block xmlns:jms-indent="jonmsterling:indenting">
  
 <jms-indent:row xmlns:jms-indent="jonmsterling:indenting">
   <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {T}\colon  \mathbf {type}\to \mathbf {type}]]></fr:tex>
  </jms-indent:row>

  
